how to develop guide / service robot

ChatGPT said:

Building a guide / service robot is totally doable if you break it into clean layers. Think of it less like one robot and more like hardware + brain + behavior + deployment
Heres a practical, end-to-end roadmap used in real projects (museums, hospitals, malls, campuses).

1 Define the robots job (this decides everything)

Before touching hardware, lock this down:

Typical guide / service roles

  • Indoor navigation (museum, mall, hospital)

  • Greeting & guiding people to locations

  • Answering questions (voice / screen)

  • Simple delivery (documents, small items)

  • Queue management / info desk replacement

Key constraints

  • Indoor or outdoor?

  • Fully autonomous or semi-autonomous?

  • Human interaction level (voice only vs touch screen vs gestures)

  • Budget range?

Example

Indoor guide robot for a shopping mall, voice + touch screen, autonomous navigation, no manipulation

2 Hardware architecture (robot body)

Core components

ComponentCommon choices
BaseDifferential drive (2 wheels + caster)
MotorsDC motors with encoders
ControllerSTM32 / Arduino / ESP32 (low-level)
Main computerIntel NUC / Jetson Nano / Orin
Sensors2D LiDAR, depth camera, IMU
InteractionTouch screen, mic array, speakers
Power24V Li-ion battery + BMS
SafetyEmergency stop, bumper sensors

Recommended starter stack

  • LiDAR: RPLIDAR A2 / S1

  • Depth camera: Intel RealSense D435

  • Main compute: Jetson Orin Nano

  • MCU: STM32 for motor control

3 Software stack (the robots brain)

Operating system

  • Ubuntu 20.04 / 22.04

  • ROS 2 (Humble / Iron) industry standard

Core software modules

mathematica

  - TTS

  - Task planner

 Hardware Drivers

  - Sensors             
  - Power

4 Navigation (hardest but critical)

SLAM (mapping)

  • slam_toolbox (ROS 2, highly recommended)

  • Cartographer (more complex environments)

Localization & planning

  • Nav2 stack

    • AMCL

    • DWB / RPP planners

    • Behavior Treebased navigation

Indoor best practices

  • Avoid glass-only walls (LiDAR issues)

  • Add visual landmarks if space is repetitive

  • Use speed limits around humans

5 Human interaction (guide robot magic )

Speech recognition

  • Offline: Vosk, Whisper

  • Cloud: Google Speech, Azure Speech

Text-to-speech

  • Coqui TTS

  • Festival

  • Cloud voices (more natural)

Dialog system

  • Rule-based (state machine) reliable

  • LLM-powered (ChatGPT / local LLM) flexible

  • Hybrid (recommended)

Example flow:

vbnet
Human: "Where is the restroom?"
Robot:
   Intent detection
   Look up POI
   Navigate + talk

6 UI & experience design (often underestimated)

Good guide robots

  • Talk less, show more

  • Confirm before moving

  • Explain what theyre doing

UI options:

  • Touch screen (HTML / Qt / Flutter)

  • Animated face (simple eyes work!)

  • LED status rings

7 Safety & compliance (non-optional)

  • Emergency stop (physical button)

  • Max speed 1.0 m/s indoors

  • Obstacle detection redundancy

  • Failsafe stop on sensor failure

If commercial:

  • ISO 13482 (service robots)

  • Local regulations (Japan/EU differ)

Phase 3 Interaction (12 months)

  • Voice recognition

Phase 4 Field testing (ongoing)

  • Human behavior tuning

  • Error recovery

  • Reliability improvements

You said:
how to develop vision parts for those kinds of robot

ChatGPT said:

Great questionvision is what turns a moving kiosk into a smart hotel / tour robot
Ill focus on practical, production-grade vision, not research fluff.

1 What vision actually means for hotel / trip robots

You do NOT need full autonomous driving vision.
You DO need reliable, explainable perception.

Core vision tasks (priority order)

  1. Human detection & tracking (safety + interaction)

  2. Obstacle detection (backup to LiDAR)

  3. Face detection (NOT recognition, usually)

  4. Gesture detection (optional)

  5. Visual landmarks (navigation support)

  6. Crowd density estimation (advanced)

2 Sensor choices (hotel-friendly)

Recommended sensors

TaskSensor
Depth + peopleRGB-D camera (RealSense D435 / D455)
Wide awarenessFisheye RGB camera
RedundancyLiDAR (primary nav)

Avoid monocular-only vision for safety.

Mounting

  • Height: 90120 cm

  • Tilt: slight downward

  • Field of view covers feet + torso

3 Vision software architecture

markdown
Camera
  
Preprocessing
  - Rectification
  - Depth alignment
  - FPS throttling
  
Perception Modules
  - Person detection
  - Obstacle detection
  - Face detection
  - Gesture detection
  
Fusion & Logic
  - Human proximity
  - Following target
  - Safety zone
  
Robot Behavior

ROS 2 nodes per module = best practice.

4 Human detection (MOST IMPORTANT)

Best approaches (2025-ready)

MethodNotes
YOLOv8 / YOLOv9Fast, accurate
Depth-assisted filteringReduces false positives
Skeleton trackingOptional (OpenPose / MediaPipe)

Pipeline example

arduino
RGB image  YOLO person detection
Bounding box  Depth ROI
Estimate distance
Publish /human_pose

Why depth matters

  • No size guessing

  • Stable distance estimate

  • Safer stop zones

5 Obstacle detection (vision backup)

LiDAR is primary. Vision is failsafe.

Vision methods

  • Depth thresholding

  • Ground plane removal

  • Optical flow (advanced)

Safety zones

ZoneDistanceAction
Warning1.5 mSlow
Caution1.0 mVoice alert
Stop0.5 mFull stop

6 Face detection (hospitality-safe)

DO

  • Face detection (presence, attention)

  • Head pose estimation (looking at robot)

DO NOT (usually)

  • Face recognition (privacy, legal issues)

Tools

  • MediaPipe Face Detection

  • OpenCV DNN

  • YOLO face models

Use this for:

  • Auto-wake screen

  • Greeting trigger

  • Language hint (optional)

7 Gesture & follow me vision

Follow-me mode

Simple & reliable approach

  • Detect person

  • Lock target by depth + position

  • Ignore re-ID across long occlusion

Gesture detection

  • Hand raise = start

  • Palm stop = stop

Tools

  • MediaPipe Hands

  • Skeleton tracking (optional)

Keep gestures very limited.

8 Visual landmarks (navigation helper)

Hotels have:

  • Long identical corridors

  • Repetitive textures

Add vision landmarks

  • QR markers

  • AprilTags

  • Visual logos

Use them to:

  • Correct localization drift

  • Confirm POI arrival

9 Lighting & real hotel issues

Problems you WILL face

  • Night lighting changes

  • Sunlight through glass

  • Reflections

  • Crowds blocking view

Mitigations

  • Auto-exposure lock

  • Depth confidence filtering

  • Slow robot speed

  • Vision + LiDAR fusion

Performance targets (realistic)

ModuleTarget
Camera FPS1530
Person detection 15 FPS
End-to-end latency< 200 ms
Detection range0.34 m
False stop rate< 2%

On Jetson

  • TensorRT

CPU fallback

  • OpenVINO

  • INT8 quantized models

Vision stack

  • image_pipeline

AI

documents, devices, environments, procedures, and deployment artifacts for hotel / travel guide robots.

Below is a full development & documentation framework you can actually use as a checklist.

1 Overall development structure (big picture)

Think in 5 parallel tracks, not a single project:

mathematica
A. Product & Requirement Docs
B. Hardware & Devices
C. Software & System Environment
D. Physical Environment Preparation
E. Operation, Safety & Compliance Docs

If one track is missing deployment fails.

2 A. Product & requirement documents (FIRST)

These are created before building.

2.1 Product Requirement Document (PRD)

Purpose: Align engineers, hotel staff, and management.

Contents:

  • Target use case (hotel lobby / tour site)

  • User types (guest, staff, admin)

  • Supported languages

  • Robot tasks (guide only / follow-me / delivery)

  • Non-goals (important!)

Example:

diff
Robot shall:
- Greet guests in 4 languages
- Guide guests to hotel facilities
- Stop within 0.5 m of people
Robot shall NOT:
- Enter guest rooms
- Perform face recognition

2.2 Use Case & Scenario Document

Write human stories, not technical ones.

Example:

markdown
Scenario: Guest asks for breakfast
1. Guest approaches robot
2. Robot detects presence
3. Robot greets in detected language
4. Robot explains location + time
5. Robot asks to guide

This becomes your acceptance test later.

2.3 Functional Requirement Specification (FRS)

More technical, but still readable.

Sections:

  • Navigation

  • Vision

  • Audio

  • UI

  • Network

  • Fail-safe behavior

3 B. Devices & hardware documentation

3.1 Hardware Architecture Document

Include:

  • System block diagram

  • Power flow

  • Network topology

  • Sensor placement diagrams

Example sections:

diff
- Compute unit: Jetson Orin Nano
- Motor controller: STM32
- Sensors: LiDAR, RGB-D camera
- Interfaces: USB, CAN, Ethernet

3.2 Bill of Materials (BOM)

This is critical for scaling.

  • Supplier

  • Lead time

  • Replacement alternatives

3.3 Assembly & Maintenance Manual

For technicians, not engineers.

Include:

  • Exploded diagrams

  • Cable routing

  • Battery replacement steps

  • Cleaning instructions (VERY important for hotels)

4 C. Software & environment documentation

4.1 Software Architecture Document

Include:

  • ROS 2 node graph

  • Data flow diagrams

  • Inter-process communication

Example:

bash

Document exact versions:

TensorRT: 8.x
Python: 3.10

This prevents works on my machine disasters.

4.3 Deployment Environment Document

Hotel IT teams care about this.

Include:

  • Network ports used

  • Wi-Fi requirements

  • Offline mode behavior

  • Cloud dependency list

4.4 Data & Privacy Policy (VERY IMPORTANT)

Especially for hotels.

Define clearly:

  • What data is collected

  • What is NOT stored

  • Retention period

  • Camera usage policy

Example:

pgsql
Camera images are processed in real-time.
No images or videos are stored.
No biometric identification is performed.

You said:
how to integrate between person and guide/service robot

ChatGPT said:

Integrating people guide/service robots is really about HumanRobot Interaction (HRI).
In hotels and tourism, success is not about smarter AIits about clarity, trust, and social comfort.

Below is a practical integration framework used in real hotel / trip robots.

1 Think in interaction layers (human robot)

css
Human
  Presence (Im here)
  Attention (Im talking to YOU)
  Intention (What I want)
  Confirmation (You understood me)
  Trust (I feel safe following you)

Every integration method must support at least 3 of these.

2 Core interaction channels (combine, dont choose)

A. Proximity & presence (zero effort)

How humans start interaction without thinking

  • Robot detects person nearby

  • Screen wakes up

  • Subtle greeting animation

Tech:

  • Depth camera / LiDAR

  • Distance threshold (1.52 m)

Rule:

Never speak first unless eye contact or stop detected

B. Visual interaction (MOST reliable)

Primary channel in hotels

  • Large touch screen

  • Big buttons

  • Multilingual text

  • Simple icons

Why it works:

  • Quiet environments

  • Language barriers

  • Accessibility

Best practice:

  • Always mirror voice answers on screen

  • Never require typing

C. Voice interaction (secondary, natural)

Used when it adds value

Use voice for:

  • Simple questions

  • Yes / No confirmations

  • Explanations during guidance

Avoid voice for:

  • Complex input

  • Names, room numbers

  • Crowded lobbies

Golden rule:

Voice starts interaction, screen completes it

D. Motion-based communication

People read robot motion emotionally.

Examples:

  • Slow approach = polite

  • Small rotation = attention

  • Backing up = apology

Never:

  • Start moving without confirmation

  • Turn sharply near people

3 Interaction states (VERY important)

Robots should not be always listening.

Recommended state machine

scss
Idle
  (person detected)
Awake
  (attention confirmed)
Listening
  (intent understood)
Confirming
  (user agrees)
Acting (guiding / explaining)
 
Idle

This prevents confusion and mistrust.

4 Intention understanding (keep it simple)

Use intent categories, not free chat

diff
INTENT:
- location_query
- facility_info
- tour_start
- help_request

Match intent fixed action.

Use LLMs ONLY to:

  • Rephrase

  • Clarify

  • Translate

Never let LLM decide robot movement.

5 Confirmation is mandatory (people need control)

Bad:

Follow me. (robot moves)

Good:

The restaurant is on the 2nd floor.
Would you like me to guide you there?

[ YES ] [ NO ]

This single step reduces complaints massively.

6 Follow-me integration (high-risk, high-value)

Safe follow-me logic

  • Lock target by distance + position

  • Stop if target lost for 35 seconds

  • Verbal confirmation every turn

Robot says:

Please stay behind me. If you stop, I will stop.

This sets expectations.

7 Social rules robots MUST follow

Hotel etiquette rules (hard-coded)

  • Yield to humans always

  • Apologize when blocked

  • Thank guests who wait

  • Never scold or correct humans

Example:

Sorry, Ill wait here.

These phrases matter more than AI accuracy.

8 Accessibility & inclusivity

Integration must work for:

  • Elderly guests

  • Children

  • Wheelchair users

  • Non-native speakers

Do this by:

  • Adjustable text size

  • Subtitles always on

  • Slow speech mode

  • Physical height-friendly screen angle

9 Staff robot guest integration

Robots should support staff, not replace them.

Best practice:

  • Call staff button

  • Robot introduces human help

  • Staff can pause or override robot

This builds trust internally.

Measuring success (dont guess)

Track:

  • Interaction completion rate

  • Abandoned interactions

  • Guide acceptance rate

  • Stop-trigger events

  • Guest feedback keywords

If guests smile but dont follow integration failed.

Common integration failures

Robot talks too much
Moves without asking
Voice-only interaction
Over-anthropomorphism
Ignoring staff workflows
